  "risk_regime": {
    "stance": "risk_on",
    "conviction": 68,
    "rationale": "8 of 10 members are structurally risk_on (convictions 55-85, mean ~72); the only two non-risk_on are the academic researchers (Thaler, Roughgarden) who explicitly hold 'no_view' on markets rather than disagreeing. So there is no genuine bearish camp \u2014 the split is 'risk_on' vs. 'no market view.' Crucially, this is a builder/structural posture ('still early', stagnation is the real risk, internet-circa-1997 analogy), NOT a near-term price or market-timing call. It is uniformly tempered (not reversed) by near-term caution on US regulation and a shared hostility to leverage/speculation/memecoins \u2014 long-term conviction high, near-term play-defense.",
    "provenance": "grounded"
  },
  "notes": "Consensus weights coverage \u00d7 conviction and de-weights lone or stale voices. STRONGEST, broadest signals: bullish zk, ai-crypto, l2-scaling (each 5-6/10, zero dispersion); bearish crypto-policy/regulation (4/10) and speculation/casino-culture (high conviction). ETH is the only token with multi-member agreement, and even there every member frames it as technology/structure, not price \u2014 so token-level conviction is intentionally capped. EXPLICITLY SPLIT items reported as neutral/low-conviction: mev (-0.33 mean sign), BTC (-0.33), and decentralization (despite high mean conviction, stance dispersion 0.94 \u2014 Eddy/Guy add 'degrades to centralization' and 'efficiency cost' caveats against Daren/Miles cheerleading). Single-member high-conviction theses (decentralized-internet-infra 97/Dixon, nft-brands-community 95/Kominers, consensus-protocol-design 92/Roughgarden, depin 90/Guy, snark-security/Thaler) are retained but faded for lack of breadth. A structural caveat across the whole desk: these are 10 a16z builders/researchers/lawyers, not traders \u2014 the corpus is overwhelmingly thesis-, technology-, and legal-driven, so 'excitement/concern' map to conviction in sectors and designs, not return forecasts. No items were invented; all names reuse members' exact item labels."
